article.headline: Tennessee 83, Notre Dame 59
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Notre Dame turnovers and Shyra Ely's
first-half scoring was enough for third-ranked Tennessee.

Ely scored 20 points and Ashley Robinson added 14 Sunday in the
Lady Vols' 83-59 win over the No. 17 Irish.

The Lady Vols (2-0) seized the lead early while the Irish (2-3)
struggled with shooting and defense.

Notre Dame also had 14 turnovers in the first half, and
Tennessee converted several of those into easy points.

"I thought our defensive pressure in the first half was pretty
solid," Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.

On one play, Ely knocked the ball lose near the high post and
some Notre Dame players and Tennessee's Loree Moore fell on the
floor trying to scoop it up. Moore got the ball and tossed it up.
Ely caught it and went in for an easy layup, giving the Lady Vols a
17-5 lead with 13:39 remaining in the first half.

"It's always fun to be rewarded with a score, a defensive stop
when you hustle like that," Ely said.

Notre Dame is 0-16 against the Lady Vols, the only opponent the
Irish have played at least 10 times and never beaten.

Notre Dame didn't have much of a chance after Tennessee went
ahead 20-7 with 11:35 left in the first half.

"We just couldn't seem to find our rhythm offensively, and they
were able to force us into many mistakes," Irish coach Muffet
McGraw said.

Notre Dame cut the lead to 10, but the Lady Vols had a 13-2 run
to push the lead to 21.

Ely had two easy baskets during the spurt, which was capped by
Moore's layup off a clever play by LaToya Davis.

Davis went for a steal off Le'Tania Severe, and came up with the
ball as they raced to the basket. Davis had to stop to get control
of the ball and quickly passed to Moore, who was running toward the
basket.

McGraw called timeout afterward.

Severe scored three straight baskets, but they didn't help the
Irish much because Ely blew by defenders for two more layups.

"I thought Shyra Ely just had a great first half. She really
set the tone for the game," McGraw said. "Whether we were in man
or zone we really couldn't guard her."

Notre Dame couldn't get any closer than 20 in the second half.
The Lady Vols went up 56-30 with 14:58 left after McGraw was called
for a technical foul and Tennessee's Shanna Zolman made both free
throws.

Zolman scored 13 points and Tasha Butts added 10 for the Lady
Vols.

Notre Dame star Jacqueline Batteast had a better game against
Tennessee than the last time the teams met, but couldn't make much
of a difference.

She finished had 16 points to lead the Irish. Megan Duffy had
two late 3-pointers to finish with 14 points, and Severe added 13.

Batteast fouled out after scoring just two points in the teams'
last meeting, a 77-61 victory for Tennessee last December.

"I always say I want her to play well, but for us to win," Ely
said.
